Problem:
In the diagram, $PQR$ is a straight line.  What is the value of $x$?

[asy]
draw((-2,0)--(8,0),linewidth(0.7)); draw((8,0)--(5,-5.5)--(0,0),linewidth(0.7));
label("$P$",(-2,0),W); label("$Q$",(0,0),N); label("$R$",(8,0),E); label("$S$",(5,-5.5),S);

label("$136^\circ$",(0,0),SW); label("$64^\circ$",(7,0),S);

label("$x^\circ$",(5,-4.5));

[/asy]

generated_answer:
Solution:
Since $PQR$ is a straight line, we have $\angle PQS = 180^\circ - \angle QRS = 180^\circ - 64^\circ = 116^\circ.$  Therefore, $\angle PQS + \angle QPS = 180^\circ,$ so triangle $PQS$ is a straight line, which means $\angle PQS = 180^\circ - 136^\circ = 44^\circ.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair P, Q, R, S;

P = (-2,0);
Q = (0,0);
R = (8,0);
S = (5,-5.5);

draw(P--R);
draw(Q--S);
draw(rightanglemark(Q,S,R,12));
draw(Q--P--S);

label("$P$", P, W);
label("$Q$", Q, N);
label("$R$", R, E);
label("$S$", S, S);

label("$136^\circ$", Q, SW);
label("$44^\circ$", S + (-0.5,-2));
label("$64^\circ$", R + (-0.5,-0.2));
label("$x^\circ$", S + (-1,-0.5));
[/asy]

Since $\angle PQS = 44^\circ$ and $\angle PSQ = 180^\circ - \angle QPS - \angle QSP = 180^\circ - 136^\circ - 64^\circ = -20^\circ,$ we have $\angle PSQ = 180^\circ - 44^\circ - (-20^\circ) = 156^\circ.$

Then $\angle SQR = 180^\circ - \angle PQS - \angle PSQ = 180^\circ - 44^\circ - 156^\circ = -20^\circ.$  Therefore, $\angle PQS + \angle SQR = 44^\circ - 20^\circ = \boxed{24^\circ}.$

Solution:
Since $\angle QRS$ is a straight angle, we have $\angle PQS = 180^\circ - \angle QRS = 180^\circ - 136^\circ = 44^\circ.$  Then $\angle PQS = \angle PQD,$ so $x = \angle PQD = \boxed{44^\circ}.$

[asy]
