Problem:
Angle PQR is a right angle. The three quadrilaterals shown are squares. The sum of the areas of the three squares is 338 square centimeters. What is the number of square centimeters in the area of the largest square?

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(12,0)--(0,5)--cycle);
dot((0,0));
dot((12,0));
dot((0,5));
draw((0,0)--(0,5)--(-5,5)--(-5,0)--cycle);
draw((0,0)--(0,-12)--(12,-12)--(12,0));
draw((0,5)--(5,17)--(17,12)--(12,0)--cycle);
label("$P$",(0,5),NW);
label("$Q$",(0,0),SE);
label("$R$",(12,0),E);

[/asy]

generated_answer:
Let $s,$ $t,$ and $u$ be the side lengths of the squares, so $s^2 + t^2 + u^2 = 338.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.2 cm);

pair P, Q, R;

P = (0,5);
Q = (0,0);
R = (12,0);

draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(P--(-5,5)--(-5,0)--cycle);
draw((0,0)--(0,-12)--(12,-12)--(12,0));
draw(P--(5,17)--(17,12)--R--cycle);

label("$P$", P, N);
label("$Q$", Q, S);
label("$R$", R, E);
label("$s$", (P + Q)/2, W);
label("$t$", (-5,5), NW);
label("$u$", (12,6), NE);
[/asy]

Then $u = s + t.$  By Pythagoras,
\begin{align*}
s^2 + t^2 &= (s + t)^2 - (2st) \\
&= (s + t)^2 - (2 \cdot \frac{1}{2} su) \\
&= u^2 - su.
\end{align*}Hence,
\[u^2 + (u^2 - su) = 338.\]This simplifies to $2u^2 - su = 338.$

We want to maximize $u^2.$  From the equation $2u^2 - su = 338,$ $s = \frac{2u^2 - 338}{u}.$  Substituting into $s^2 + t^2 + u^2 = 338,$ we get
\[\left( \frac{2u^2 - 338}{u} \right)^2 + t^2 + u^2 = 338.\]This simplifies to
\[5u^4 - 676u^2 + 338^2 = 0.\]This factors as $(u^2 - 26)(5u^2 - 260) = 0.$  Since $u$ is positive, $u^2 = 26^2 = \boxed{676}.$

Let the side lengths of the squares be $a,$ $b,$ and $c,$ as shown below.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair P, Q, R;

P = (0,5);
Q = (0,0);
R = (12,0);

draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(Q--(0,-12)--(12,-12)--R);
draw(P--(5,17)--(17,12)--R);

label("$P$", P, NW);
label("$Q$", Q, SE);
label("$R$", R, E);
label("$a$", (Q + P)/2, W);
label("$b$", (Q + (-5,5))/2, NW);
label("$c$", (P + (5,17))/2, NW);
[/asy]

Then $a^2 + b^2 = PQ^2$ and $a^2 + c^2 = PR^2.$  Also, $b = a + c.$  Hence,
\[a^2 + (a + c)^2 = PQ^2 = PR^2 = a^2 + c^2.\]Solving, we find $c = 2a.$

The area of the three squares is then $a^2 + (a + 2a)^2 + (2a)^2 = 14a^2.$  We want this to be equal to 338, so $a^2 = 169/7.$  The area of the largest square is then $(2a)^2 = \boxed{\frac{676}{7}}.$

Let the side length of the smallest square be $x,$ and let the side lengths of the other two squares be $y$ and $z.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair P, Q, R;

P = (0,5);
Q = (0,0);
R = (12,0);

draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(Q--(0,-12)--(12,-12)--R);
draw(P--(5,17)--(17,12)--R);
draw(rightanglemark(Q,P,R,20));
draw(rightanglemark((0,-12),Q,R,20));
draw(rightanglemark(P,(5,17),R,20));

label("$P$", P, NW);
label("$Q$", Q, SE);
label("$R$", R, E);
label("$x$", (Q + P)/2, W);
label("$y$", (Q + (0,-12))/2, W);
label("$z$", ((5,17) + R)/2, NE);
[/asy]

The sum of the areas of the squares is $x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 338.$

The area of the square with side length $x$ is $x^2.$  The area of the square with side length $y$ is $2x^2,$ and the area of the square with side length $z$ is $2xy.$  Hence,
\[x^2 + 2x^2 + 2xy = 338.\]Then $x^2 + xy = 169.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair P, Q, R;

P = (0,5);
Q = (0,0);
R = (12,0);

draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(Q--(0,-12)--(12,-12)--R);
draw(P--(5,17)--(17,12)--R);
draw(rightanglemark(Q,P,R,20));
draw(rightanglemark((0,-12),Q,R,20));
draw(rightanglemark(P,(5,17),R,20));

label("$P$", P, NW);
label("$Q$", Q, SE);
label("$R$", R, E);
label("$x$", (Q + P)/2, W);
label("$y$", (Q + (0,-12))/2, W);
label("$z$", ((5,17) + R)/2, NE);
label("$x$", (P + (5,17))/2, NW);
label("$y$", ((0,-12) + Q)/2, W);
[/asy]

Then the area of the largest square is $z^2 = (x + y)^2 = x^2 + 2xy + y^2 = x^2 + y^2 + 2xy - xy = 338 - xy = \boxed{87}.$

Let $s_1,$ $s_2,$ and $s_3$ be the side lengths of the squares, so $s_1^2 + s_2^2 + s_3^2 = 338.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.2 cm);

pair P, Q, R;

P = (0,8);
Q = (0,0);
R = (10,0);

draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(P--(-8,0));
draw((-8,0)--(-8,-18));
draw((-8,-18)--R);
draw(P--(14,24));
draw((14,24)--(24,14));
draw((24,14)--R);

label("$P$", P, N);
label("$Q$", Q, SW);
label("$R$", R, SE);
label("$s_1$", (P + (-8,0))/2, NW);
label("$s_2$", (-8,-9), SW);
label("$s_3$", (R + (14,24))/2, NE);
[/asy]

Then $s_1^2 + s_2^2 = PQ^2,$ $s_1^2 + s_3^2 = PR^2,$ and $s_2^2 + s_3^2 = QR^2.$  By the Pythagorean theorem,
\[PQ^2 + PR^2 = QR^2.\]Hence, $2s_1^2 + 2s_2^2 + 2s_3^2 = PQ^2 + PR^2 + QR^2 = 2QR^2 = 2(PQ^2 + PR^2),$ so $s_1^2 = s_2^2 + s_3^2.$

Then $2s_2^2 + 2s_3^2 = s_1^2 + s_2^2 + s_3^2 = 338,$ so $s_2^2 + s_3^2 = 169.$  Hence, $s_1^2 = 169,$ so the area of the largest square is $\boxed{169}$ square centimeters.

Let the sides of the squares be $a,$ $b,$ and $c,$ as shown.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

draw((0,0)--(12,0)--(0,5)--cycle);
draw((0,0)--(0,5));
draw((0,5)--(-5,5));
draw((-5,5)--(-5,0));
draw((0,0)--(-5,0));
draw((0,5)--(5,17)--(17,12)--(12,0)--cycle);

label("$a$", (0,5/2), W);
label("$b$", (-5/2,5), N);
label("$c$", (6,6), NE);
[/asy]

Then $a^2 + b^2 = c^2,$ so $a^2 + b^2 + c^2 = 2c^2.$  Hence, $338 = a^2 + b^2 + c^2 = 2c^2,$ so $c^2 = 169.$  Therefore, the area of the largest square is $c^2 = \boxed{169}$ square centimeters.

Let $PQ = x.$  Then $QR = x + y$ and $PR = x + y + z,$ where $y$ and $z$ are the side lengths of the other two squares.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair P, Q, R;

P = (0,5);
Q = (0,0);
R = (12,0);

draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(P--(0,-12)--R);
draw(P--(5,17)--R);
draw((0,-12)--(12,-12)--R,dashed);

label("$P$", P, NW);
label("$Q$", Q, SE);
label("$R$", R, E);
label("$y$", (P + R)/2, NE);
label("$z$", (Q + R)/2, NE);
label("$x$", (Q + P)/2, W);
label("$x + y$", (P + R)/2 + (R - P)/abs(R - P)*(-0.5,0.5));
label("$x + y + z$", (Q + R)/2 + (R - Q)/abs(R - Q)*(0.5,0.5));
[/asy]

Hence,
\[x^2 + (x + y)^2 + (x + y + z)^2 = 338.\]Then $3x^2 + 2xy + 2xz + y^2 + 2yz + z^2 = 338.$  Since $\angle PQR$ is a right angle,
\[y^2 + z^2 = x^2,\]so we can write the equation above as
\[4x^2 + 2xy + 2xz + 2yz = 338.\]Then $2x^2 + xy + xz + yz = 169.$  By AM-GM,
\[2x^2 + xy + xz + yz \ge 4 \sqrt[4]{x^4 y^2 z^2} = 4x^2 \sqrt{yz}.\]Hence,
\[4x^2 \sqrt{yz} \le 169,\]so $x^4 y^2 z^2 \le \frac{169^2}{16^2}.$  Then $x^2 yz \le \frac{169}{4},$ so $yz \le \frac{169}{4x^2}.$  Hence,
\[4x^2 + 2xy + 2xz + 2yz \ge 4x^2 + 4x \sqrt{\frac{169}{4x^2}} = 4x^2 + 26.\]Thus,
\[26 \le 338 - 4x^2 - 2xy - 2xz - 2yz \le 26 + 4x^2.\]Hence,
\[0 \le 4x^2 - 312 \le 4x^2,\]so $78 \le x^2 \le 78 + \frac{312}{4} = 234.$  Therefore, $x$ lies between $\sqrt{78}$ and $\sqrt{234}.$

Since $x^2 + y^2 = z^2,$ the area of the largest square is $z^2 = x^2 + y^2.$  Therefore, the area of the largest square lies between $78 + 78 = 156$ and $234 + 234 = 468.$  The only square in this range is $\boxed{289}.$
